##ICU in the wee hours: being alive means everything

The nurses adjusted the endotracheal tube for the patient. They used disposable gloves to make a stent for the catheter and wrote a message of blessing. Photographer: Lu Xiang

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Reporter: He Wu

Cold Room, warm night.

The 73 year old critically ill patient with midazolam pneumonia has been in a coma for days -- as low as 60% of her Oxygenation -- under the constant influence of a sedative, mucus filling her lungs.

Every four hours, the nurses give her a sedation score and test her response by patting and calling her name. In her most dangerous time, the Department of Critical Care Medical Director Fan Xuepeng connected her to the hospital's only ECMO (artificial lung) . The one million yuan device takes over a patient's lungs outside of the body, pumps oxygen through veins to the patient's organs and releases carbon dioxide.

This is the scene in the negative pressure room of the ICU on the 3rd floor of Wuhan First Hospital. It's dangerous, it's wrapped up in layers. The mortality rate for those who enter the facility is 67% .

After walking through the Empty Hall on the first floor, fan reached the door of ICU on the third floor by escalator. The nurses who handed out the supplies had already prepared protective equipment, and he had to be careful to wear them in strict accordance with the procedure, to avoid any part of the exposure to high concentrations of the virus. The whole process usually takes 30 minutes. With the nurses writing their names on each person's chest and back, fan calls it BOSS Fan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The nurses write their names on each other for easy identification. Photographer: Lu Xiang

He pushed open the Blue Door and there was another world. In this 20-square-meter ICU room, patients are surrounded by machines and catheters. A nasal airway penetrated 23 centimeters into her body and a gastric tube 100 centimeters into her intestines. She doesn't know anything about any of this.

She is still in danger, but her condition has improved. The sedative that forced her into a coma has been reduced to 40 milligrams per hour to increase her physical activity. During the routine search, Fan patted the patient's arm, called her name, and came close to her, opening the other's eyelids. Patient's not responding.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 3:00 a.m. , Fan Xuepeng was explaining his work to the patient. Photographer: Lu Xiang

The nurses began to turn over the patients. This is usually their first job after shift change. To avoid bedsores from prolonged bed rest, nurses use pillows to change the patient's position so that her body is turned in a different direction. The patient is empty so the catheter can be inserted. She came to a standstill like a ship, silent and heavy. To "preserve the dignity of the patient, " nurses covered her private parts with a blue blanket as they rolled her over -- a common practice in the ICU.

Another convention is about the power of time. ICU negative pressure room by a number of lights, except blue, white, no other color. The monitoring equipment and catheters are cold, the blood needle is cold, and only the unconscious patient on the sickbed is hot. These two negative pressure wards have no windows and the doors are always closed. For the critically ill, time outside doesn't make sense. Once the patient's vital signs are completely stable and he or she has regained consciousness, the nurses said, they try to minimize interruptions at night, leaving only a small orange light by the bed "so that they know day and night. "

It takes four nurses to roll over. The men in the suits were drenched in sweat. There was only the sound of the instruments in the room, but when they talked, they had to be close to each other.

As the nurses rolled the patient over, her right foot trembled slightly, and she slowly opened her eyes. The nurse hastily called Fan Xuepeng who was checking the medical records on the computer outside the door. He looked at her again, and their eyes met. Fan knew that the 73-year-old patient's condition was gradually stabilizing. Her friend, a 57 year old in a pressure ward next door, was getting better, too. The lack of oxygen from her new pneumonia caused her to open her eyes unconsciously, and nurses placed wet gauze over her eyes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Nurses operate sophisticated monitoring equipment. Photograph: Lu Xiang

"To be alive means everything, " said the chief of critical care medicine, who has been practicing medicine for more than a decade.

Right now, knowledge of the new coronavirus is still limited. The scary thing about the new coronavirus, Fan said, is that there is no specific drug. "Most people heal on their own. " Oxygen therapy, nutritional supplements and antibiotics are key. After the SARS epidemic, the consensus was not to use large doses of hormones. "This time the consensus is not to use steroids for everyone. "

He witnessed the Wuhan epidemic from the beginning to the outbreak, and now "bed and so on" the entire process. Following the outbreak of "unexplained pneumonia" in late December 2019, Fan, as one of the business leaders, led his colleagues from the hospital to many places to participate in the treatment of designated patients in Wuhan's Fifth Hospital, Raytheon Mountain Hospital. Later, he returned here to help set up the first hospital for new pneumonia patients admitted to the ward.

The hospital, which is located in the center of the epidemic area, established the standard fever clinic very early. On Jan. 5, the first day of the outbreak, a hospital centralized the management of suspected cases in various departments, and asked the doctors to wear protective clothing. On January 10, Fan Xuepeng also found several cases in the clinic and had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market. He reminded colleagues to pay attention to the clustering pattern of cases. These measures have significantly reduced the risk of infection among hospital staff. Up to now, only 3 of the 80-plus medical staff in the Department of critical care have been infected, and all of them have mild cases. Now, they're all cured and back on the team.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fan Xuepeng observes the patient's condition. Photograph: Lu Xiang

Now, it was not the most exhausting time for him. On New Year's Eve on January 24, Fan, accompanied by eight doctors and more than 20 nurses, arrived at Wuhan's Fifth Hospital and treated 60 patients overnight. After 24 hours of continuous work, they were nearly exhausted when they left the cabin.

He usually enters the isolation ward at 9 am, leaves the cabin at noon, attends the consultation meeting in the afternoon, handles the management work. The patient's symptoms changed, he also had to be ready to enter the cabin, simply in the opposite hospital is still open hotel opened a room, in the shortest possible time to the ward.

This wasn't his night shift. He still chose to make late-night rounds to see "the real thing at night" , to check on patients and to be with his staff. He feels, Wuhan is now a frontline nurse more scarce than the doctor, "Know Your comrade-in-arms, understand their hard work. "

He sent his son back to his hometown in Huanggang, Hubei Province early. The son is 14 years old, and he and his son video call each day to talk about their day. Even in protective clothing, doctors and nurses are still afraid after an outbreak, Fan said. "The fall of the self is secondary, the fall of the family is fatal. "

To avoid the risk, most nurses also choose to stay in the hospital temporarily. They were housed in a three-person room that had been vacated. Cheng Shiyu, a nurse, also sent her 20-month-old son to his home in Caidian District, while her husband stayed at home in Wuchang. They also usually make video calls at 7 pm. The couple is often silent, watching the screen son eat, play.

It's the longest she's ever been away from her son. The first few days of separation -- as if on a New Year's Eve, when Cheng Shiyu sees her mother holding her son in the video -- she cries.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Nurses must constantly monitor the signs of critically ill patients. Photographer: Lu Xiang

More than a month later, mother and son are also used to such a way to meet. Her parents showed their grandchildren pictures of her in protective clothing: "look, it's mom. " The son developed the perception that every time he watched people in protective clothing on the front lines of the epidemic on television, he would point to the screen and shout:

"Mom. "

Cheng Shiyu has known her husband for five years. They would continue to talk for a while after their son went to bed. The hostess would instruct her husband to do the housework at this time. Every time he used to come here, he'd try to fight back. Now, he would say yes to her. They haven't seen them for months, Cheng said, and the epidemic has profoundly changed them.

The nurses usually arrive at the ward at 1:30 a.m. After the patient is turned over, they also need to draw blood, refill the pump, or do pneumatic treatment to prevent long-term bedridden patients with venous thrombosis.

They will also continue to monitor the patient's vital signs. In general, routine monitoring of body temperature and blood sugar ranges from one to four hours. For critically ill patients, important indicators such as Oxygenation require constant testing. That means nurses need to keep an eye on the numbers. They recorded all the changes that had taken place in the patients'physical signs in order to inform the doctor's judgement.

Now, two patients in the negative pressure ICU, physical signs have gradually stabilized, doctors and nurses will usher in the most difficult time.

When they are busy, Cheng says, they don't feel the tedium inside the suits or the fatigue on their bodies. "when they relax a little, all kinds of pain follow. " Their clothes are already soaked, and they can smell the rancid smell of their bodies in their suits. If you wear a mask for long periods of time, it will cut your ears like a knife. When they stop moving and doing physical labor, they feel the cold close to their clothes. At 5 a.m. , they were generally hungry and thirsty, with stomach pains. But these feelings, they can't be expressed. Physical pain can be transmitted like an "infectious disease" to others present.

Fan xue-peng did not show his pain. As the night's work drew to a close, he returned to his desk. It was nearly 6 o'clock and the morning shift doctor Zhang pushed open the door of the ward. They came to the two patients'beds, Fan Xuepeng gave her detailed account of the next 4 hours of attention to details.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the penultimate paragraph, Fan Xuepeng's photographs are displayed outside his hospital room. Photographer: Lu Xiang

He then withdrew from the ward. He used to take pictures of foreign landscapes when he was studying abroad, and hung them in the corridor of his department. These landscapes from Boston, the Netherlands and elsewhere are framed in red. As he walks through the landscape in his Hazmat suit, he looks up at these vibrant natural objects.
